<div class="container">
    <h1>Types of Databases</h1>
    <p>Now that you understand what a database is, let’s explore the different types of databases and what they’re used for.</p>

    <h2>1. Relational Databases (SQL)</h2>
    <p>This is the most common type. Data is stored in tables, like spreadsheets, and tables can be connected with relationships. Examples include:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Microsoft SQL Server</li>
        <li>MySQL</li>
        <li>PostgreSQL</li>
        <li>Oracle Database</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Use when:</strong> Your data is structured and needs relationships (like Users, Orders, Products).</p>

    <h2>2. NoSQL Databases</h2>
    <p>NoSQL databases are designed for flexibility. They don’t use tables like relational databases. Types of NoSQL databases include:</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Document-based</strong> (e.g. MongoDB)</li>
        <li><strong>Key-Value</strong> (e.g. Redis)</li>
        <li><strong>Column-based</strong> (e.g. Cassandra)</li>
        <li><strong>Graph-based</strong> (e.g. Neo4j)</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Use when:</strong> You have large or rapidly changing data that doesn’t fit neatly into tables.</p>

    <h2>3. In-Memory Databases</h2>
    <p>These databases store everything in memory (RAM), which makes them super fast. An example is Redis.</p>
    <p><strong>Use when:</strong> Speed is critical, like for caching or real-time apps.</p>

    <h2>4. Cloud Databases</h2>
    <p>These databases are hosted on the cloud (like Azure, AWS, or Google Cloud) and are easy to scale.</p>
    <p><strong>Use when:</strong> You want flexibility, automatic backups, and easy access over the internet.</p>

    <h2>5. Flat File Databases</h2>
    <p>These are basic text files (like CSVs). Simple and used for very small applications.</p>
    <p><strong>Use when:</strong> You don’t need complex structure or performance.</p>

